    "question": "What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous replication?",
    "ground_truth": "According to [1], [2], [4], [5], [7], [9], [13], [16], [17], [18], [19], and [20], the main differences between synchronous and asynchronous replication are:\n\n* Synchronous replication uses a separate clock signal (or pulse) to synchronize data transmission, whereas asynchronous replication relies on special signals or transitions in a single signal to synchronize data transmission.\n* In synchronous replication, the receiver detects the \"first\" edge transition of the signal to determine when another bit is ready. In contrast, in asynchronous replication, the receiver uses transitions on a single signal to figure out the transmitter's bit rate and timing, and sets a local clock using a phase-locked loop (PLL) to synchronize with the transmission rate.\n* Synchronous replication typically requires a constant \"bit\" timing, whereas asynchronous replication can tolerate some variation in timing.\n\nIn general, synchronous replication is more suitable for applications that require strict timing and synchronization, such as real-time systems or high-performance computing. Asynchronous replication, on the other hand, is often used in distributed systems where latency and variability are acceptable, such as in cloud computing or big data processing.",
